I always took it as she ran away from the story she was telling Emily and Pam, because she had a shit family. Charlotte offered to pay her to toy with other people‚Äôs lives, and given Sara‚Äôs past with treating her friends like shit, she went along with it. Then once she got close to the liars to be a spy after the dollhouse, she grew genuine feelings for Emily, and began to be kind of a double agent.

I guess she was pissed at the liars for what happened to her hands, but let‚Äôs be real, that wasn‚Äôt their fault. Girl was just cray. That and Marlene needed a reason to keep her around as a suitable red hearing for the new big bad. It was stupid.

When it came time to reveal the big mysteries in season 6, I think the writers realized that A was going to have needed an accomplice to pull off everything they did. Not that this show is big on realism to begin with, but I suppose they were making an effort lol. They knew the mystery of Sara Harvey was still an open case, and decided to use her to fill some gaps. It backfired on them by only creating more holes in the story. I don‚Äôt think they ever explicitly answered certain questions about Sara because they expected us to just be so floored by the revelation of her being Red Coat and BW, that we wouldn‚Äôt want anything more from it.

However, they should know us PLL fans dig deep, and analyze everything. We wanted to know why Sara ran away, how she met Charlotte, and why she stayed. Considering they never gave any of these questions a thought cause they figured we were gonna be happy with the surface level answers of her being the accomplice that all would be good. Lololol didn‚Äôt turn out that way at all.

This is something I‚Äôve had to come to terms with ever since being diagnosed bipolar at the beginning of the year. In the past I‚Äôve mostly worked in the medical field, and while I loved it, I didn‚Äôt tend to last more than a couple years at one place. 

My last job I was working as a flight attendant at a very reputable airline, and that‚Äôs when the mania came and showed it‚Äôs nasty head. I spiraled into the worst manic episodes of my life. 

After being fired (which was a first for me,) I‚Äôve gone through a few different gigs, but am doing better now that I‚Äôm on the right meds, in therapy, and attending a regular support group. 

It‚Äôs not perfect by any means, but I am feeling inclined and ready to return to work full time. It‚Äôs a scary thought, but I‚Äôm ready to face it. I‚Äôve been caregiving part time, and just got offered a full time gig. So here‚Äôs to what‚Äôs next! 

Keep on keeping on my fellow bipolar warriors!
